#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // With 2n students, if we sort them, the optimal strategy is to
        // assign the first n students to one class and the next n students to another.
        // The median of the first class will be a[n-1] (if it has n elements, and n is odd).
        // The median of the second class will be a[n] (if it has n elements, and n is odd).
        //
        // More generally, if we sort the array a, the median of any class of size 2k+1
        // will be one of the elements in a.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array: a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // We need to pick two medians, say M1 and M2.
        //
        // If we split the sorted array into two halves:
        // Class 1: a_0, ..., a_{n-1}
        // Class 2: a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}
        //
        // Each class has exactly n students.
        // If n is odd, then this is a valid partition.
        // The median of Class 1 (a_0, ..., a_{n-1}) is a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of Class 2 (a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}) is a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        //
        // However, the problem statement implies that the sizes of the classes
        // can be different, as long as they are both odd.
        // For example, if n=3 (6 students), classes could be (1,5), (3,3).
        //
        // The key insight for this type of problem is that to minimize the difference
        // between medians, the medians themselves should be as close as possible
        // in the sorted array.
        //
        // Let the sorted array be $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // Consider any partition into two classes, $C_1$ and $C_2$, with sizes $S_1$ and $S_2$.
        // $S_1, S_2$ are odd, $S_1+S_2=2n$.
        // Let $m_1$ be the median of $C_1$ and $m_2$ be the median of $C_2$.
        //
        // It can be shown that the minimum difference is always achieved when the two medians
        // are adjacent elements in the sorted full array, specifically $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        //
        // To prove this:
        // Let $m_1$ be the median of $C_1$ and $m_2$ be the median of $C_2$.
        // Suppose $m_1 < m_2$.
        // For $m_1$ to be the median of $C_1$ (size $2k_1+1$), there must be $k_1$ elements $\le m_1$ and $k_1$ elements $\ge m_1$.
        // For $m_2$ to be the median of $C_2$ (size $2k_2+1$), there must be $k_2$ elements $\le m_2$ and $k_2$ elements $\ge m_2$.
        //
        // Consider the element $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ in the sorted full array.
        //
        // If we choose $a_{n-1}$ as the median of one class and $a_n$ as the median of the other class,
        // we can always construct such a partition.
        //
        // For example, let $C_1$ contain $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and $C_2$ contain $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // Each class has $n$ elements.
        // If $n$ is odd, this is a valid partition. The median of $C_1$ is $a_{(n-1)/2}$ and $C_2$ is $a_{n+(n-1)/2}$.
        // This is not necessarily $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than that.
        // The minimum difference between medians of two odd-sized classes is always $|a_n - a_{n-1}|$.
        //
        // Let's try to construct a partition for $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ to be the medians.
        // We need to form two classes $C_1$ and $C_2$ of odd sizes $S_1, S_2$.
        // Let $a_{n-1}$ be the median of $C_1$ and $a_n$ be the median of $C_2$.
        //
        // Class $C_1$:
        // We need $k_1$ elements smaller than or equal to $a_{n-1}$ and $k_1$ elements larger than or equal to $a_{n-1}$.
        // We can pick $a_{n-1}$ itself.
        // We have $n-1$ elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$ that are $\le a_{n-1}$.
        // We have $n$ elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ that are $\ge a_n > a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Let's try to make $a_{n-1}$ the median of $C_1$ and $a_n$ the median of $C_2$.
        //
