        // The parity of (abs_n + abs_m) must match the parity of `abs_n - abs_m`.
        // (abs_n + abs_m) % 2 == (abs_n - abs_m) % 2. This is always true.
        //
        // After `abs_n` moves, we are at (abs_n, abs_m).
        // We have `remaining_moves` moves left.
        // Each pair of moves (e.g., (1,0) then (-1,0)) can be used to return to the same spot.
        // Each such pair of moves changes the total number of moves by 2, but doesn't change the final position.
        // So, if `remaining_moves` is even, we can use all of them to make pairs of moves that cancel out.
        // If `remaining_moves` is odd, we must make one extra move.
        // This extra move will change the parity of the final position.
        // So, if `remaining_moves` is odd, and we are at (abs_n, abs_m), we must end up at a point (x', y')
        // where (x'+y') % 2 != (abs_n+abs_m) % 2.
        // But we need to end up at (abs_n, abs_m). This means if `remaining_moves` is odd, it's impossible.
