        // This is because each move changes the sum of coordinates by an amount that has the same parity as the move type (0 for diagonal, 1 for straight).
        // No, this is not correct. Each move changes the parity of x or y or both.
        // (x_new + y_new) % 2 = (x_old + dx + y_old + dy) % 2 = (x_old + y_old + dx + dy) % 2.
        // So, (x_new + y_new) % 2 == (x_old + y_old) % 2 if (dx+dy) is even (diagonal move).
        // (x_new + y_new) % 2 != (x_old + y_old) % 2 if (dx+dy) is odd (straight move).
        //
        // Starting at (0,0), (0+0)%2 = 0.
        // After K moves, we are at (abs_n, abs_m).
        // Let `s` be the number of straight moves.
        // The parity of (abs_n + abs_m) will be `s % 2`.
        // So, (abs_n + abs_m) % 2 must be equal to `s % 2`.
        //
        // We want to maximize diagonal moves, so minimize straight moves.
        // Minimum straight moves `s_min` is `abs_n - abs_m`.
        // If `k - abs_n` is even, we can make `(k - abs_n) / 2` pairs of cancelling moves.
        // Each pair can be two straight moves (e.g., (1,0) then (-1,0)) or two diagonal moves (e.g., (1,1) then (-1,-1)).
        // Or one straight and one diagonal (e.g., (1,0) then (0,1) to reach (1,1) in 2 moves, instead of one (1,1) move).
        //
        // The key insight is that after `abs_n` moves, we are at (abs_n, abs_m).
        // We have `k - abs_n` moves left. These moves must effectively cancel out to keep us at (abs_n, abs_m).
        // Each such "cancelling" move must be paired with another move that brings us back.
